\noindent\textbf{Key observation.}
The few-shot output is structurally superior to zero-shot---it reads
like a real consult note---but is substantially less faithful.
Adding same-language demonstrations introduced four fabricated
entities (caregiver name, comorbidity, drug name, smoking history)
and inverted the frequency of two stated risk factors.
The zero-shot output hallucinated pathologies (apnea) and timelines
(three days), but did not invent a different patient's clinical history.
This illustrates the entity-bleed mechanism (T3): the demonstrations
introduced a structural prior \emph{and} specific clinical content
that contaminated the test summary.

\subsection*{Case B: Translation Condition (scenario\_1)}

\noindent\textbf{Clinical context.}
A 46-year-old patient undergoing radiotherapy for head and neck cancer.
Consultation covers side effects, laboratory investigations (CBC, ESR,
immune function), HPV vaccination eligibility (up to age 45, with
clinician discretion for exceptions), tobacco use and cessation,
conditional procedure planning, and result timelines.

